That&#39;s where the &quot;All Swing applications must run on their own thread&quot; part comes. Take a look at [initial threads][1] and [the Event Dispatch Thread][2]. Starting your application by calling `SwingUtilities#invokeLater` will solve your problem.

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -&gt; {
			JFrame f = new JFrame(&quot;Menu&quot;);
			f.setVisible(true);
			f.setSize(400, 400);
			f.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

			JMenuBar menubar = new JMenuBar();

			JMenu file = new JMenu(&quot;File&quot;);
			JMenu tools = new JMenu(&quot;Tools&quot;);
			menubar.add(file);
			menubar.add(tools);

			JMenuItem exit_item = new JMenuItem(&quot;Exit&quot;);
			tools.add(exit_item);

			f.setJMenuBar(menubar);
		});
	}

I also advice you to `frame.setVisible(true)` after the whole frame is prepared:

	SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -&gt; {
		JFrame f = new JFrame(&quot;Menu&quot;);
		f.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

		//add stuff to frame

        f.setSize(400, 400);
		f.setVisible(true); //Here at the end
	});


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/concurrency/initial.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/concurrency/dispatch.html

